<paragraph blockId="2.[454,809,215,239]" box="[454,809,215,239]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<heading bold="true" box="[454,809,215,239]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[454,809,215,239]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
Key to Genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1886" box="[657,809,215,239]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ammophilini">Ammophilini</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[401,862,270,292]" box="[401,862,270,292]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">(from BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976, slightly modified)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="309" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
1 Episternal sulcus curving back to scrobe from subalar fossa, then extending obliquely ventrad to anteroventral area of mesopleuron (
<figureCitation box="[662,718,332,354]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); New World forms............................ ............................................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="MENKE" authorityName="MENKE" box="[883,1086,355,376]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Eremnophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[883,1008,355,376]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Eremnophila</emphasis>
MENKE
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
- Episternal sulcus extending straight down from subalar fossa (in some species absent), not passing through scrobe (
<figureCitation box="[487,546,408,430]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).....................................................................................2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">2 Claws in most specimens simple but if with single basal tooth on inner margin then mouthparts very long, galea attaining base of stipes when folded......................................3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">- Claws with one or two basal teeth on inner margin; galea not extending beyond stipes midlength when folded and in most specimens shorter; Old World forms..........................4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
3 Apex of sternum I (petiole) meeting and in many specimens overlapping base of sternum II (
<figureCitation box="[333,393,569,591]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); spiracle of tergum I located before apex of sternum I (in profile); petiole in many specimens bent upward at level of base of tergum I ......... 
<taxonomicName authority="FERNALD" authorityName="FERNALD" box="[890,1086,591,613]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[890,990,591,612]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Podalonia</emphasis>
FERNALD
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
- Apex of sternum I not reaching base of sternum II, intervening space mostly long and consisting of membrane and ligament (
<figureCitation box="[620,685,645,667]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); spiracle of tergum I located at or beyond apex of sternum I; sternum I in many specimens bent downward or straight at level of base of tergum I.................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="W. KIRBY" authorityName="W. KIRBY" authorityYear="1798" box="[872,1086,690,712]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ammophila" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[872,983,690,711]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Ammophila</emphasis>
W. KIRBY
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
4 Mesothoracic venter with anteromedian projection behind forecoxa; petiole socket nearly completely surrounded by propodeal tergum (
<figureCitation box="[751,814,744,766]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); inner orbits of female markedly converging below; midtibia with single spur ................... 
<taxonomicName authority="GRIBODO" authorityName="GRIBODO" box="[862,1086,766,788]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Eremochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[862,990,766,787]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Eremochares</emphasis>
GRIBODO
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
- Mesothoracic venter without anteromedian projection, at most obtusely angled (exception: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Beaumont" baseAuthorityYear="1956" box="[332,571,820,841]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Parapsammophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foleyi">
<emphasis box="[332,571,820,841]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Parapsammophila foleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); petiole socket broadly bounded ventrally by Tshaped propodeal sternum (
<figureCitation box="[495,559,842,865]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); inner orbits of female only slightly converging below or parallel or diverging below; midtibia with two spurs (one may be reduced or absent).................................................................................................................................5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
5 Foretarsomere I of female markedly asymmetrical, its outer apex prolonged (
<figureCitation box="[984,1046,919,941]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); free margin of male clypeus rounded or truncate; male gonostyle of usual shape ................ ......................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="TASCHENBERG" authorityName="TASCHENBERG" box="[763,1085,964,986]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Parapsammophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[763,940,964,985]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Parapsammophila</emphasis>
TASCHENBERG
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[178,1086,309,1062]" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="309">
- Foretarsomere I of female nearly symmetrical, outer apex only slightly produced (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); male clypeus triangular; male gonostyle of unusual shape: 
<figureCitation box="[827,892,1018,1040]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="74.[178,218,1474,1496]" captionTargetBox="[218,1020,220,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@74.[178,1048,220,1460]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I- II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280417/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
................................. ............................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="de BEAUMONT" authorityName="de BEAUMONT" box="[785,1085,1040,1062]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Hoplammophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[785,941,1040,1061]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="309">Hoplammophila</emphasis>
